./.title: Home
./.body:
üöÄüêü Spacefish




A Fish Shell prompt for Astronauts.

Spacefish is a Fish Shell port of Spaceship; the minimalistic, powerful and extremely customizable Zsh prompt. It combines everything you may need for convenient work, without unnecessary complications, like a real spacefish.
Features

Indicator if user is root
Prompt character turns red if the last command exits with non-zero code.
Execution time of the last command if it exceeds 5 seconds.
Current Node.js version, through nvm/nodenv/node (‚¨¢).
Current Ruby version, through rvm/rbenv (üíé).
Package version, if there's is a package in current directory (üì¶).
Current Git branch and rich repo status:
? ‚Äî untracked changes;
+ ‚Äî uncommitted changes in the index;
! ‚Äî unstaged changes;
¬ª ‚Äî renamed files;
‚úò ‚Äî deleted files;
$ ‚Äî stashed changes;
= ‚Äî unmerged changes;
‚á° ‚Äî ahead of remote branch;
‚á£ ‚Äî behind of remote branch;
‚áï ‚Äî diverged chages.


Current battery level and status:
‚á° - charging;
‚á£ - discharging;
‚Ä¢ - fully charged.



Upcoming features

Displaying hostname/username
Indicator for jobs in the background (‚ú¶).
Current Python pyenv (üêç).
Current Ruby version, through chruby/asdf (üíé).
Optional exit-code of last command.
Optional time stamps 12/24hr in format.

Want more features? Please, open an issue or send pull request.
Preview

  


Requirements
To get spacefish working correctly you will need:

fish (v2.7.0 or newer)
Powerline Font must be installed and enabled in your terminal.

Installation
Fisherman
$ fisher matchai/spacefish

Oh My Fish!
$ omf install spacefish

Customization
Spacefish works well out of the box, but you can customize almost everything if you want.

Options ‚Äî Tweak section's behavior with tons of options.

You have the ability to customize or disable specific elements of Spacefish. All options must be overridden in your config.fish.
Troubleshooting
Having issues? Take a look at our Troubleshooting page.
Still struggling? Please file an issue, describe your problem, and we will gladly help you.

docs/Options.html.body:
Options
You have ability to customize or disable specific elements of Spacefish. All options must be overridden in your config.fish.
Colors for sections can be basic colors or color codes.
Note: the symbol ¬∑ in this document represents a regular space character  , it is used to clearly indicate when an option default value starts or ends with a space.
Order
You can specify the order of prompt section using SPACEFISH_PROMPT_ORDER option. Use Zsh array syntax to define your own prompt order.
The order also defines which sections that Spacefish loads. If you're struggling with slow prompt, you can just omit the sections that you don't use, and they won't be loaded.
The default order is:
    set SPACEFISH_PROMPT_ORDER user dir git node exec_time line_sep battery char

Prompt
This group of options defines a behavior of prompt and standard parameters for sections displaying.



Variable
Default
Meaning




SPACEFISH_PROMPT_ADD_NEWLINE
true
Adds a newline character before each prompt line


SPACEFISH_PROMPT_SEPARATE_LINE
true
Make the prompt span across two lines


SPACEFISH_PROMPT_FIRST_PREFIX_SHOW
false
Shows a prefix of the first section in prompt


SPACEFISH_PROMPT_PREFIXES_SHOW
true
Show prefixes before prompt sections or not


SPACEFISH_PROMPT_SUFFIXES_SHOW
true
Show suffixes before prompt sections or not


SPACEFISH_PROMPT_DEFAULT_PREFIX

Default prefix for prompt sections


SPACEFISH_PROMPT_DEFAULT_SUFFIX

Username (user)
By default, a username is shown only when it's not the same as $LOGNAME, when you're connected via SSH or when you're root. Root user is highlighted in SPACEFISH_USER_COLOR_ROOT color (red as default).



Variable

Meaning

SPACEFISH_USER_PREFIX
with¬∑

SPACEFISH_USER_COLOR

SPACEFISH_USER_COLOR_ROOT
red
Color of user section when it's root



SPACEFISH_USER_SHOW defines when to show username section. Here are possible values:

Show on remote

always

Package version (package)

Works only for npm at the moment. Please, help spaceship improve this section!

Package version is shown when repository is a package (e.g. contains a package.json file). If no version information is found in package.json, the ‚ö† symbol will be shown.

Note: This is the version of the package you are working on, not the version of package manager itself.

Node.js section is shown only in directories that contain package.json file, or node_modules folder, or any other file with .js extension.
